The Eastern Illinois University College of Education is now recruiting candidates for its Accelerated Post-Baccalaureate Teacher Licensure Program.

The program is for adults who have completed a bachelor's degree and can complete an eight-week course of study during Summer 2021 on EIU's campus in Charleston, followed by a one-year, full-time residency in a secondary school.

Content areas and grade ranges offered in the program include:
Mathematics (grades 9-12)
Science (Biology, Chemistry, Earth Science, Physics) (grades 9-12)
English (grades 9-12)
History-Social Science (grades 9-12)
Career and Technical Education (Business, FCS, Technology) (grades 6-12)
Foreign Language (French, German, Spanish) (grades K-12)
More information may be found at www.eiu.edu/coe/accelerated.php

Northside PE had over 40 participants for their Live River on the Bank Challenge!
In the River, on the Bank is a challenging mind game where students must react quickly. They follow along to the video/audio commands of when to jump “in the river” or back “on the bank”. There are 5 different levels to the game, and each level gets more challenging. Students were challenged to see how few mistakes they could make, with an end goal of having as low of a score as possible.

https://youtu.be/Q-2_YkasPWU

Please join the Northside Family in welcoming Samantha Stocking to Northside Elementary School. Samantha had this to say about herself:

"Hello, my name is Samantha Stocking and I am from Buda, Illinois. This spring I graduated from Illinois State University with a bachelor’s in science of education with a specialty in special education and an endorsement in early childhood special education.

I enjoy spending my free time riding horses, being outdoors, and being with my friends and family. I love to spend my weekends at the lake during the summer. I really enjoy taking vacations to the mountains where I can be outdoors all the time.

I spent my summer giving horseback riding lessons, nannying for three kids under 4, and my weekends at the lake which is also where I got engaged this summer.

I am very excited to begin my special education teaching career in Geneseo as the Early Childhood Special Education Teacher."

Please join Northside Elementary School in welcoming Amanda Ray to the Northside family. Miss Ray had this to say about joining Northside:

I am really excited to start off my teaching career in 4th grade at Northside. My dream job since I was in 3rd grade was being a teacher. I am originally from Downers Grove, IL but recently graduated from Augustana College in May with a Bachelor of Arts in Elementary Education. In college I was a part of the Augustana softball team where I had the opportunity to travel to Brazil this past winter to experience their culture and compete against their national team.

My favorite teams are the Chicago Blackhawks, the Chicago Bears and the Chicago White Sox. I love to spend time at the beach or lake. My favorite two vacation spots are South Haven, MI and Minocqua, WI. My favorite color is blue and my favorite food is chocolate.

post_text:
Please join us in welcoming Mrs. Kate Reed, the new guidance counselor at Geneseo Middle School!!!
Mrs. Reed grew up in Geneseo, attending Millikin Elementary, Geneseo Junior High, and graduating from Geneseo High School. She completed her Bachelor's Degree at Augustana College and earned a Master's Degree in School Counseling from Western Illinois University, Quad Cities. After starting her career in the Prophetstown School District, Mrs. Reed has spent the past five years in the Pleasant Valley School District.
"I am looking forward to starting my 16th year as a School Counselor and getting to know students and families! I am so honored to be a part of the excellent staff at GMS as well as the high level of achievement for which our district is known," said Mrs. Reed. "My favorite teams include all those who wear Geneseo green! You will see my family and me supporting the Maple Leafs!!! It brings me great joy to be home again!"
Mrs. Reed enjoys bike riding and playing tennis with her family as well as baking.

The Illinois Department of Human Services has launched a support line called Call4Calm that is reachable via text. Individuals who want to speak with a mental health professional can text the word “TALK” or “HABLAR” (for Spanish speakers) to 552-020. Within 24 hours, that individual will receive a call from a mental health professional employed by a local community health center.

People can also text other terms, like “unemployment” or “food” or “shelter” to the same number to receive information on how to navigate and access supports and services. Call4Calm is free, and individuals who use it can remain anonymous.

On May 23, the Illinois General Assembly passed Senate Bill 2135, which in part amended the Open Meetings Act to permit, and set conditions for, conducting board meetings by audio or video conference without the physical presence of board members. As a result, the Geneseo CUSD 228 school board meeting will be held “virtually” on Thursday, June 11, 2020 at 5:00.

The public may still participate by joining the meeting by phone (1-570-783-1294;‬ PIN: ‪144 309 316‬#) or through Google Meet at: meet.google.com/cxw-btia-xws. The agenda for the meeting can be found on the district website at https://geneseoschools.org/board-of-education/ . Questions about the meeting or accessing the meeting may be directed at Jill Hamer at jhamer@geneseoschools.org.

post_text: Congratulations to Kay McAvoy, GMS 8th grade student, who was selected by the Illinois State Art Education Association to have her work exhibited for the State All Student Show. Mr. Hamilton was just informed of the honor and shared that, “This show is a big deal. It is the equivalent of a state sports or band competition. It is a juried show where a panel of artists choose which works will be selected and displayed. Out of all the districts and grade-levels in the state, only 45 artworks are selected and Kay is going to represent Geneseo!” Her artwork will be on display around the state as part of a traveling art exhibit. Way to go Kay!!! We’re proud of you and will miss you and your classmates as you take your talents to GHS next year.

post_text:
Due to the Governor’s Stay-at-Home order, the Geneseo CUSD 228 school board meeting will be held “virtually” on Thursday, May 14, 2020 at 5:00.

Recognizing that some meetings are necessary during this time, the Governor has suspended the requirement that a quorum of the members of a public body be physically present at a board meeting and the conditions which limit when remote participation is permitted. This means that:

- A public body may convene a properly noticed meeting with any number of members physically present, or no members physically present, as long as the total participating members constitutes a quorum; and

- No specific reason or vote to allow for remote participation is required.

The public may attend the meeting remotely by computer or phone using the Google Meet platform. Directions on how to login or dial in, as well as the meeting's agenda, can be found on the district website at https://geneseoschools.org/board-of-education/. Questions about the meeting or accessing the meeting may be directed at Jill Hamer at jhamer@geneseoschools.org.

post_text: Our Food Service Department works hard to make sure our students have the opportunity to receive two free meals each day since the initial shutdown on March 17. Because of their service and demonstration of Teach - Learn - Care to our families, each received a Maple Leaf Medallion today.

post_text:
The Northside 5th grade students completed a Penny Wars project during the month of December. They collected money as a donation to charity. Each 5th grade student researched charities and wrote a persuasive essay about one charity to convince their classmates where the money should be donated. Taefyl Freeman persuaded the 5th grade boys to donate $104.30 to the University of Iowa Stead Family Children's Hospital. Mia Balensiefen persuaded the 5th grade girls to donate $76.26 to the Henry County Humane Society.

Attached is a group photo with the winners in center. The other photo is a representative from the Henry County Humane Society accepting the girl's check.
